div.div:
It would be inefficient to derive SI entries from a snapshot that doesn't contain the oldest commit versions, because every SI entry depends on the delta between the previous PV and the current PV for the same PK. Therefore, SICr works on the whole PI dataset in the commit version range ( -inf ~ snap_commit_ver_hi_excl ).
Steps:
The job reads a PI snapshot; k-merges the nodes; and retrieves non-tombstone (PK,PV) entries.
The (PK,PV) stream is not ordered by SV. Hence the job sorts in memory (in a Memtable without a write-ahead log); and flushes periodically into new internally-sorted files (without SSTable's in-memory component).
The job k-merges the incrementally-produced temporary files into one SSTable.
The job creates a new node, and inserts it.

Impl option 1:
For each node :
Copy memory into the new node.
We can wrap node contents in Arc(s). But then we should make sure that only the SI deletion operation modifies the Arcs' atomic counters, and no other operation does.
Hard-link files into the new node. (On-disk equivalent of Arc::clone().)
Impl option 2:
Do not explicitly delete anything. Leave memory and files in place.

SIs are creation-in-progress.)
If a SI for a given SVSpec is deleted then re-created ...
Option A: SICr builds in this fashion ...
1. Override lingering data. K-merge existing data; then, for every entry, put a tombstone in SICr's output.
2. K-merge primary entries. (Then follow steps for SI creation.) These data override the above overriding of lingering data.
Option B: Each new SI is given a new identity, even if previously another SI existed for the same SVSpec.
(We need a unique integer identifier for each SI anyway, for naming things in filenames (though in the future we might depend less on semantically meaningful filenames).)
We go with option 2 B.

div.div:
Concurrent SICr jobs:
In order for 2+ SICr jobs to operate concurrently correctly :
The F+C worker ought to receive requests instructing to "F+C below the speicfied node" in the same order as the corresponding fence dummy nodes were pushed.
If the receipts are mis-ordered, then the system still works correctly; but the system fails to guarantee to pre-process (ie F+C) all SICr jobs' snapshots.
In conclusion:
Pragmatically, it's reasonable to require dbadmins to request SICr jobs one at a time. Hence, to avoid increasing the complexity of the impl,
we choose to execute SICr jobs sequentially
.

div.div:
Notifying the F+C worker at the end:
The LL _may_ be F+C'able, for any of these reasons:
Within the SICr's snapshot, held nodes may have become non-held. If so, the snapshot is newly F+C'able.
The SICr's snapshot's head dummy node (was a fence; no longer a fence), may be non-held, and if this node is not the LL head, then this dummy and non-dummies around it are newly eligible for F+C.
There is no mechanism to precisely determine whether the LL is indeed newly F+C'able.
Notifying is not required for correctness.
We choose to always notify.

div.div:
Premise:
SICr takes a long time; hence its snapshot is not GC'able for a long time.
Goals:
SICr's snapshot must not be GC'd.
--> To save resources (memory + disk), SICr's snapshot ought not be F+C'd.
--> Hence SICr's snapshot ought not include any MemLogs.
The LL portions outside any SICr's snapshot should remain F+C'able and GC'able.
Solution:
F+C flushes the entire current list (and optionally compacts it). Only after this does SICr start working.
SICr does not hold any list ver. The list ver concept continues to apply to the LL portions outside any SICr's snapshot.
SICr's snapshot is marked as non-traversable to F+C, using the `fence` variable in dummy nodes.
